##Diary of a plague victim: If I make it this far, it will be out of anger

World-views

Introduction to the function, re-understanding the world

After the traffic stopped, I urged Anna to contact the embassy. She's British and German. I want her to take the baby out. At first, she didn't register as an emergency. She was unfazed, more submissive than the rest of us, and said, it doesn't matter, I've taken it for granted since running away in December. Six months ago, we moved from England to Australia. At the end of the year, threatened by wildfires, closed at home, outside is thick smoke. In early January, back in Wuhan, once again experienced a shortage of masks. She's on a schedule to extend her stay in solitary.

First there's the American evacuation. Charter flights. Then the French evacuation of overseas Chinese, Charter, to Changsha. Anna said, how can we fall behind the French. She chased some letters to the German embassy and contacted the British embassy. We are in close communication, the German said. The British say we have no plans to evacuate the colony. Since then, "close communication" has become a daily joke, referring to vague resistance and difficulties. Anna's anxiety began on the second day of the Lunar New Year, January twenty-six, when a two year old child in Guangxi Province was diagnosed. Our child is not yet three years old. Before this, we said that will not infect the child, to comfort the heart, who dare not be sure. The virus has finally broken the age barrier. Anna's parents are in Germany, they don't sleep, daily phone calls and emails.

In Britain, where the evacuation plan was launched, Anna made phone calls and entered his identity and contact information. She said, "I put your message in. They said the family can go together. ". I said, Anna, if you can go, I'll stay. My parents, my grandmother, they're still here. Young people are most likely to survive the virus. I'm staying here until the lockdown is over. I understand, Anna said. A never-ending discussion begins at home. My father said, "if you can walk, walk. ". What are you going to do if you stay. I said, I'm taking a long vacation. The mother asks, what do you want to stay. He didn't want to be called a deserter. I mean, take a break. You guys look great.

We're concerned about cross-contamination on the plane, two weeks after landing. From Australia to Wuhan, Anna said, he stayed at home for more than a month. It's almost a week since Wuhan was shut down. Two more weeks in isolation, the baby's GONNA go crazy. He hates hospitals. When Anna Thought of it, he was emotional, and his faith was irreconcilable. At first I thought, 'this isn't about me, this isn't just about me, ' she said. 'Now I'm starting to think it might be about me. '. Every seemingly irrational panic, in the end, was justified. I said, "don't worry. You can't change it. You stay calm, you stay steady. ". She said, "you can't teach me to take my time. I can hold on for a while, but I can't hold on forever. ". If we had known and left sooner, we could have avoided all of this. It's too late for that now. I'm sick of this cowardice, my cowardice, the public cowardice, everyone's cowardice. If I make it to the end this time, it's all in anger. I mean, I don't think anyone here is weak. You know, people trying to get on with their lives, doctors and nurses on the front lines. If we both stayed, I wouldn't worry too much. She said, I don't mean any of that. It's our panic in a crisis, our loss of logic, our loss of reason. Why don't you look at the international reports of pneumonia in Wuhan.

I haven't been exposed to foreign news. This is in stark contrast to previous attitudes towards events. It could be a daily overload, it could be the eye of the storm, and you don't feel the need. I don't even know from which day Wuhan became the International Focus. I began to read foreign reports in the morning, holding my breath, no less than at night to watch the domestic news. It's not like writing about a disaster, it's writing about Karma. The discussion of evacuating overseas Chinese questions why some people go to Wuhan, and those who want to come back are kept away from it for a long time, so as not to cause a national disaster. Officials have abandoned rapid testing and home quarantine, imposed quarantine on returnees, restricted entry and calmed the public. I see what Anna meant by cowardice. I fear that even if I leave safely, my child will be subject to unknown hostility and ostracism because of who he is. For a moment, I said to myself, I might as well stay, but then I gave up the idea of being angry.

We live in it, she says, and we're not so stressed out. Death is closer to us. People we know are sure it's suspicious, but when no one talks about it, they think it's going to happen to them right away. When we get nervous, all we can think about is who's infected at home, who's infected at home, and what to do about it. Even if the infection, think of is, bad, relatives and friends to do, the contact of those people. People outside the epidemic area, afraid of death, are straight to their own. As if that was the only way the fear was real. We read individual stories, just like everyone else, but we never talk about them in front of our families, not to deny the desperate experiences, but to keep them close to us.

The evacuation arrangements have gone through many twists and turns. On January twenty-eight, a German request to send military aircraft was denied. It's over, Anna said. The Germans aren't coming. She went back to England and found the name was misrecorded. The person politely apologizes and types in the message again. Two days in a row, Anna said, the French did it. She can not for the life of her life believe that her two countries are lagging behind their neighbours. She spends all her time in her room, talking on the phone, e-mailing, and reading all the gossip. Her parents live in China's time zone. Finally, while the family was watching don't tell her, Anna, seated in a chair, stood up and we waited for her announcement.

The Germans are coming, she said, but we're being quarantined for two weeks. The trouble doesn't stop there. Those who leave need medical attention, but those who show symptoms should not leave. It doesn't say if the children and their families can go with them. A British evacuation plane tried to take off on the twenty-nine and was stuck at the airport for two days, with the children and their families at the centre of the dispute. China will not release any person who has Chinese nationality. Britain and Germany insist on the principle of preserving the family. I said to my parents, you see, the white discussion for so long, the Chinese people would not have walked away.

The mother turned the adult mask into a child's mask, folding it inwards and sewing it back on. Father, get the authorities to drive to the airport. Reluctantly, Anna signed off on the mandatory quarantine. I'm making a children's movie for the quarantine. Until then, we're doing everything we can to uphold the no-tv rule. Knitting Indoor activities to get through the day. Dogs and children are the hardest to understand, and they are particularly bored and irritable. Children's vocabulary is growing, in Australia to learn "fire" , in Wuhan to learn "cough" and "mask. He was surprised to find that we were stocking up on daily quotas of cookies and movies for our trips. I said, it's Chinese New Year, and it's not over yet.

The German plane had to arrive at the airport a day earlier than 8:00. Anna gets up in the morning and Turandot plays in the kitchen. I mean, is that really necessary. It's going to be a long battle, she said. On the last night of January, we set off. Traffic Lights, high-speed motorcycle. Two cars, one on the left and one on the right, were speeding down the open road. This week, traffic police have been on a round-the-clock chase to prove that traffic order did not collapse because of the outbreak. The inspectors with the lists checked at the airport tollgates before going through the military. The blast detection at the door became a temperature test. There were Koreans, Indians, Bangladeshis, Sri Lankans, Turks, Germans in the departure hall. I haven't seen this many people in days.

South Koreans, by far the biggest, occupy the empty desks and check in passengers. Three German officers showed up, wearing orange vests. They first inquired about China Southern's empty service desk, but thought that even if is the extraordinary time occupation is not appropriate. Ten minutes after they disappeared, they somehow managed to get a Chinese wooden table and two chairs. From the bag, take out the German flag on the corner of the table, began to register. Thanks to the British in front of the pull saw, the children's families can get on the plane today. A stone has been lifted from our hearts.

No one knows how long it will take, and whether the plane is on the other side of the glass. Those who fail the physical examination are led to an ambulance at the door by a doctor in full protective clothing. From eight o'clock to eleven o'clock, the child ran tired in the airport, also do not want to wear a mask. I put him to bed in the car, away from the crowds at the airport. He made me carry him in the front seat. After midnight, my arm went numb and I fell asleep until my phone rang. 3:30. Nothing. It's chilly at the airport. At first, the heavily guarded crowd was overwhelmed. They took off their masks and gloves and ate snacks and instant noodles freely. After another two hours of this, Anna said, a healthy man would get sick if he stayed like this. The Koreans left, then the Bangladeshis, then the Germans and Turks. Let's check in and get in line for a physical.

You're going to have to get him out, I said. It was not completely dark outside, and the sky began to outline itself. In Anna's arms, dressed in a red coat, he opened his eyes and said, go home, grandma and GRANDPA. None of us spoke to each other. I said, I'm not going with you and mom this time. If mom won't let you see Petch, you call me. He said, "let's go. ". I said to Anna, didn't you give him a shot. I was in a hurry, Anna said. We hadn't said much goodbye, hadn't had much rest in two days, and our mouths were dry and our heads were swollen. I said to Anna, you've finally calmed down, and you've been holding back from criticizing the Chinese. She said, "your people have said enough. ". I mean, maybe we can lift the lockdown next week, even faster than you can get out. She said, "then I'll be angry enough to leave. ". You get a good night's sleep. You'll be up till 10:00 tomorrow. I said, "all right, off you go. ".

They disappeared into white and yellow suits.

Home. Sun's up. I threw my mask in the trash, threw my clothes in the washing machine, showered, and soaped twice. I'm tired all over, but I'm wide awake. Change into clothes, as if the completion of a mission is not good or bad and win or lose. The room was empty, and the covers of the COT and the large bed were neatly folded at the foot of the bed. The night light's still on the power strip. Anna's hair was on the pillow, and she forgot her eye cream. There was shampoo and baby lotion in the room, which would soon disappear into the disinfectant. Downstairs, toys littered the living room, unfinished puzzles and Origami on the table. The morning light should have reached the stairs leading in. On the days when he couldn't go out, we allowed him to take a piece of chalk, draw pictures at the door, pass the time, and fight boredom. Walls, floors, staircases, all the colors. He painted the steps intently, tracing them, first red, then green, then purple, and so on, until the sun went down, and we called him upstairs to eat.
